The stock market is crashing... Here's how you can use it to get rich 💸 Because did you realize the most millionaires are made during times like these? First thing we need to know is corrections, those are normal. They happen once every two years. We shouldn't be surprised when they occur, we should begin to expect it, and use them to our advantage. Second thing is that most people get scared when the market crashes, and they make emotional decisions (like selling their stocks) which is actually what causes them to lose money. Because the stock market as a whole has recovered from crashes 100% of the time. (this is why we don't buy individual stocks, and we diversify + hold long term) Right now we're in and out of a bear market, and that means the market is down 20% or more from recent highs. On average, it takes about 19 months for stocks to recover their losses. But for the last three bear (or near bear) markets in 2011, 2018 and 2020, it took stocks just four to five months to make up the losses. Third thing is that the stock markets best days, where you make the most money, generally happen around the worst days. So how do you use this to your advantage? Do what the millionaires are doing. I'm dollar cost averaging my money into the stock market to take advantage of this sale. According to the Wells Fargo Investment Institute study, the average 12-month return after the end of a bear market is 43.4% You could make 43% on your money in a single year. This is not the time to be scared, it's the time to learn and take action. Instead of buying when stocks are already high, buy when they're low and ride them up - what's where you make the most money. Ready to learn? The way we speak to women about money is sexist and needs to change. 

This is the title of a Refinery 29 article, and I couldn't agree more. 

In the article the author discusses how she feels like she missed the class on how to manage money, but it seems she just woke up one day and her male peers knew how to apply for mortgages and invest in their IRAs, but she was still googling what APR meant. 

Is it that men just intrinsically know these things? 

No, no one is born knowing anything - everything, every skill, is taught and learned. 

Studies have shown time and time again that there is a difference between the ways we as a society treat women and men when it comes to money, and this extends even into our families. 

How many men have grown up hearing they just need to find a woman with a good job to marry and take care of him? 

Conversely how many women are told the same? 

It doesn't stop there. 

"A study analyzed the difference between how male and female-centric media outlets speak to their readers about money, and the results show some inherent — and problematic — differences. The study looked at 300 stories, and researchers found that women were defined as "excessive spenders" across 65% of the articles aimed at them. They were advised to “limit, restrict, and take better control of shopping 'splurges'.” In contrast, Starling Bank says, the language of the men’s articles implied that financial successes made readers “more of a man". The articles used words like "dare" to encourage men to “invest” and to "spend" to achieve “power”. Back over on the women's side though, 71% of articles encouraged women to seek out "vouchers", "discounts", "bargains and coupons" to save money." 

- Refinery29

I want to make money in stocks, should I wait for the market to recover or start now? 

In a perfect world you'd buy when stocks are at their bottom, meaning the lowest price they'll go, before they go on to surpass their previous high prices making you tons of money along the way. 

When will I know stocks are at their bottom? 

Right now for the stock market to recover the stock market needs to get out of a cyclical downturn, caused by overheated inflation and raising interest rates (which will cause the economy to contract). 

These kind of downturns usually stop when rates get cut, so people start borrowing more money and pumping it into the economy. This is likely why stocks are slightly higher last week, because people are expecting less aggressive rate hikes.

DEBT ISN'T A DIRTY WORD. In the middle class we have been taught to believe that debt is bad. That debt is mortally wrong. That we should work to become debt completely debt free. The thing is, the rich actually know that debt is a tool - it's referred to as leverage. If you can make a higher return investing your money than the cost of the debt (interest rate), then you're actually "losing money" by paying off your debt. This is part of the theory behind the strategy the rich use called: Buy Borrow Die. The rich will put their money into assets, like stocks and real estate, and use other people's money (loans) to live off of tax free. This is accomplished because the interest on the debt is lower than the return, especially when taking into consideration the taxes they would pay to remove that money as income (you don't pay taxes on debt, even if you're using it to live). If you value being debt free, that's okay too - but ask yourself: is this because that's truly what the best strategy for your money and your life is, or is it because you don't know another way?

You have money that you want to grow, but it's not for retirement. Let's talk about the different types of accounts you can use in the US and Canada to help you make more free money . First things first, before you decide anything you need to be clear about your goal - not every account or investment is right for every person. The key is to not only deposit money, but to buy investments with it. In Canada, we have a TFSA, which is an account you can use to invest and make money tax free, and there are no limitations to taking the money out. you could use this to save for a house, a car, early retirement, a gift for your kids. If you're saving for a house in Canada the new house you may want to consider the new FHSA instead and save your tfsa contribution room for other goals. In the US, if you're saving for Healthcare you could use a HSA to invest and grow your money for future expenses. if you're gifting investments to a minor you could use a UGMA. Other goals outside of traditional retirement would be invested for in a regular brokerage account. your earnings there are taxable. The main difference with these accounts is just the tax treatment, but as taxes are likely your largest expense, it's important to limit them where you can.

DON'T MAKE THIS INVESTING MISTAKE 👇👇👇 

Did you realize that your IRA (or your 401k for that matter) is NOT an investment? 

For my Canadians 🇨🇦 neither is your RRSP or TFSA. 

They are accounts that you buy investments with. 

Simply putting money into this account doesn't mean it will grow. 

You need to actually choose your investments and buy them with the money in the account. 

I've seen too many people think they're doing the right thing, when they're actually missing the most important step. 

Here's what you should be doing: 

1. Set up your account with a brokerage (they give you access to purchase investments like stocks, bonds and REITs) 

2. Transfer money into the account (pro tip: set up automatic transfers from each pay so you can stay on track with your goals) 

3. CHOOSE YOUR INVESTMENTS and purchase them with the money inside the account. 

If you're just starting out, you can look into things like target date funds and asset allocation funds for an entire portfolio in one to make things easier (because good investing is actually boring and simple). 

Then, leave it alone and let it grow. You can build incredible wealth with these accounts, but you need to make sure you're actually invested to see that compound interest magic. 

The last thing you want is to be years or decades down the road wondering why your account hasn't grown, only to find out you've missed out on the time you needed to build a fat bank account with less. 

Time is more important than money when it comes to investing. 

Don't miss out.

Money mistakes that will keep you broke, from someone who used to make them and always had $0 in her bank account.

 Thinking that my paycheck was profit, when really it was income. 

Businesses know this simple rule: how much you make is not how much you keep. 

And I’m not just talking taxes, I’m talking the cost to earn that money. 

How much are you paying for gas and transportation and licensing fees and happy hour drinks and food because you don’t have time to cook. 

Add up all those expenses and subtract them from your pay to understand how much you actually have to spend, then divide this number by the number of hours you ACTUALLY work to see your real hourly wage. 

Use this real wage to help you make purchasing decisions. 

Is that really a new sweater you don't need (and don't actually really want), or is it 3 hours of your life? 

If there's something you would have rather done for those 3 hours than working to pay for it, like going to the beach, doing yoga, or hanging out with friends... don't buy it, and invest that money instead. 

Give future you the life you wish you had today.

I make 6 figures a year without working by putting my money into investments that pay me out monthly. 

Two of my favorite investments for cash flow are REITs and MICs. 

REITs are real estate investment trusts, and this is where you buy parts of a company that owns and operates real estate - and then shares their profits with you. 

Depending on your country, to remain a REIT they need to distribute between 70-90% of their profits, so that can mean great money for the shareholders. 

REITs are easier to start for beginners, because you can get automatic diversification with REIT ETFs (Vanguard has some great ones). 

MICs are mortgage investment corporations (otherwise called asset backed lending, or private lending). 

This is where you pool your money with other investors to loan out on mortgages, and you get paid the interest (like the bank would). 

There are many MICs I wouldn't touch with a 10 foot pole as they're too risky (rule number 1 of investing: don't lose money). 

Examples of ones I wouldn't lend to would be ones that offer loans over 1 year, ones that lend on soft development costs, ones that do commercial lending, or ones that do large loans. 

Two important factors to consider if you're looking at a MIC are loan to value ratio (ie. how much of the value of the property is being lent out, the higher the riskier it is), and the mortgage position (1st mortgages are less risky than 2nd or 3rd).

A line of credit or HELOC is NOT free money. 

The only thing you should be using a LOC for is to do renovations on your property before you sell it to increase the sales price. 

Make sure you consult a professional before you decide which renovations to invest in, because many renovations do not provide a dollar for dollar return - just because you spend money doesn't mean you're going to make it back. 

I had a client that spent over $40k on "desqueaking" her floor. There was nothing wrong with the floors, but she had a new baby and wanted the home to be "squeak" free. She spent a lot of money to get this done, and unfortunately at there was nothing materially wrong with the floor before, the renovation did not add more value for the new buyer (meaning she spent this money for her own "enjoyment" but would not see a return). 

I know it's popular with real estate to use the equity in your home to purchase more properties, but especially if the LOC is secured against your SHELTER, it is much too risky. 

The equity in your home can disappear with changing home prices, and if you're financing a property with 100% debt you could be putting yourself in a very precarious position. 

Your LOC is also not free money - you should not be using this for consumer purchases, or thinking that it's an emergency fund. It's a loan, and a loan is a loan is a loan. 

Leverage can be a powerful tool when used properly (like to get an immediate return on the sale of your home), but it can also increase your losses when used improperly (and put your family's shelter at risk).

I want to talk about an important and often overlooked form of abuse: financial abuse. 

This can take many forms, but some common warning signs to watch out for include: 

Your partner is spending money on your credit card without your knowledge or consent. 

They are constantly asking you to co-sign loans or credit cards, even though you may not fully understand the financial implications. 

They are consistently asking you to cover their rent or other bills, even though they are capable of paying for these expenses themselves. 

If you're experiencing any of these red flags in your relationship, it's important to take action and seek help. 

Financial abuse can be just as damaging as physical or emotional abuse, and it's important to protect yourself and your financial well-being. 

Remember, you have the right to make your own financial decisions and to be treated with respect and equality in your relationship. If you need support, there are resources available to help you. 

Don't be afraid to reach out for help. #financialabuseawareness #relationshipadvice #domesticviolenceawareness

For a lot of us the holidays are an incredible time of family and happiness, but conversely for a lot of us the holidays are hard. 

There were quite a few years for me where the holidays just felt like a reminder for all I didn't have. 

I felt stuck in life, like I didn't have the time, energy, money or support to do the things I wanted or live the way I dreamed. I felt like no matter what I did I'd always be stuck. 

What I didn't realize is that these feelings become a self fulfilling prophecy. One of my mentors early on introduced me to Angela Duckworth and her studies on success - and what I learned was that the greatest predictor of someone's path in life was their grittiness. Through my studies I came to know this as a growth mindset. 

I'm not successful today because I had life handed to me, because I had help and support, I'm successful because I saw what needed to be done and took responsibility for each of my actions every day. 

I realized that life was always going to throw shit at me (and trust me babes, when I say I've had my fair share of shit, I'm being modest LOL), because that's life - and I could let it break me, or make me. 

At my last session after divulging more of my childhood trauma, my therapist said to me "it's almost like you had to go through all those things to learn the lessons you did, to create the beautiful life you have now". 

It allowed me to take a little solace in the reminder that I could have chosen to stay stuck, but I used those situations to know what I did NOT want in my life, so I could craft a plan to get what I did. 

And that's the thing: each "shit storm" in life is actually a lesson, every time you fail you're actually learning more about what it will take the next time to see success... 

And although we cannot ever control what happens to us, we have 100% capacity to control the actions we take afterwards. "If you're unhappy, move, you're not a tree". 

You may feel stuck in one way or another as we pass through this season, but know that you've survived 100% of the days in your life so far, and you can and will persevere moving forward.

YOUR GETTING PAID LESS THAN YOU THINK. 

Listen up y'all, let's talk about the real hourly wage. When you calculate all the hard costs that go into earning a paycheck (think licensing, transportation, work clothes, etc.), and soft costs (think vacations you need to escape, takeout you buy because you have no time, wine you get to help calm yourself down after a stressful day), it's likely a lot less than you think. 

Want to know the real number? 

Try this exercise: add up all the hard and soft costs that go into earning your paycheck for the year, divide this by 52 to get the average weekly spend. Subtract this from your weekly pay to get your balance. 

Then add up all the hours you actually work, and divide your balance by your real worked hours. 

This is your real hourly wage. 

Mind blown yet? 

Seeing this number does 2 things: 

1. It's important to understand the true cost of our labor in order to change the way we think about spending and valuing our time. Think about the things you're buying in terms of your real hourly wage - how long did you ACTUALLY have to work to buy that thing? Is there something else you'd rather have done than work those hours? Then maybe it's a sign we shouldn't buy it. 

2. Show you that although you may think you make more money in a "higher paying" job, you may actually be able to take a less stressful "lower paying job" because you'd actually net more (aka keep more in your pocket). 

I teach you how to change the way you think about money so you can use it to build your dream life, and then share the strategies I used to go from $40k debt to a millionaire at 30 so you can get here too.

TWO KEY LESSONS FOR SUCCESS AND HAPPINESS. 

Okay so I just watched a video about a woman who quit her teaching job to work at Costco. and at first glance you might be like - WHY would you leave a job you went to school for and worked so hard to get? 

but there's two key lessons I want you to take out of this that, if you master, you will have a happier and more fulfilled life.

 1. the sunk cost fallacy - ever heard the saying don't throw good money after bad? 

we have a tendency to continue on a path simply because we've already invested time and money into it. but here's the thing, if what you've been doing isn't working, the time and money you've put into it won't come back no matter how much more you put in. 

so it's actually better to cut your losses and move on. 

2. your real hourly wage - a lot of us think the number on our paycheck is what we make, but it's not. businesses understand this concept: your income is not your profit, because you had to spend money to earn that income. 

additionally, you're likely working more hours than you're getting paid for, and this doesn't account for the additional hours you stress and worry about work on your "you time". 

when you actually do the calculation most people find they're making a lot less than they thought.

Today, we're talking about money trauma and how it can impact your life. 

First, let's define what we mean by money trauma. It's not just about not having enough money or struggling with financial problems. 

Money trauma can also be the result of past experiences or beliefs about money that shape our attitudes and behaviors around it. 

Some examples of money trauma might include: 

Growing up in a household where money was a source of conflict or stress

 Experiencing financial abuse or manipulation from a partner or family member 

Feeling like you're not good with money or that you'll never be able to get ahead financially 

Being told that you're not worthy or deserving of financial success 

These types of experiences and beliefs can lead to negative patterns and behaviors around money, such as overspending, avoiding financial planning, or feeling anxious or overwhelmed by financial decisions. 

But it's important to know that money trauma is not something you have to live with forever. 

There are ways to work through and heal from these experiences, such as seeking therapy or financial coaching, building a support system of friends and loved ones, and setting healthy financial boundaries. 

This is one of the things we help our students with, and the reason they're able to have such life changing success. 

We know that being good with money is not a simple math problem, and if all you had to do was write down your expenses on a peice of paper no one would be struggling. 

This is also why we have a therapist on staff to help our students move through their mindset blocks, so when we teach them the million dollar tactic (like investing) it gets to change their entire lives - instead of cycling through old patterns that have been keeping them stuck and broke. 

So if you're struggling with money trauma, know that you're not alone and that it's possible to find healing and financial success. 

Take the first step by acknowledging your feelings and seeking support.

Listen up, if you want to knock your annual review out of the park and score that sweet raise, you need to be proactive. 

Don't make the mistake of waiting until the last minute to try and prove your worth. 

Follow these steps to set yourself up for success: 

Clarify your job duties and responsibilities with your boss and make sure you're meeting or exceeding all of your targets. 

Keep your boss in the loop on your progress and accomplishments throughout the year. 

Set up regular check-ins to remind them of your value to the company. 

Make a list of your specific achievements and contributions to the company, and be ready to quantify them with numbers and examples. 

Think about your long-term goals and how you can contribute to the company's success. 

Walk into your review with confidence and be prepared to advocate for yourself. Don't leave it up to your boss to remember everything you've done – come in with concrete proof of your worth. 

If your boss tries to brush you off by saying that everyone has room for improvement and that's why you didn't get a raise, don't buy it. 

Sometimes, the only way to get paid what you're worth is to leave your current company and find one that values you more. 

Remember, job hopping can actually increase your income because new companies often have bigger budgets to attract top talent. 

Don't be afraid to consider your options if it means getting the recognition and compensation you deserve.

Is fear of failure holding you back? 

Today we're gonna talk about the fear of failure and where it comes from. 

But first, let's define what the fear of failure is - it's the feeling of anxiety or discomfort that comes up when we think about the possibility of not achieving our goals or not succeeding. 

It's the feeling that tells us we're not good enough, or that we'll never be successful. 

So, where does this fear come from? It often originates from past experiences and limiting beliefs that we've picked up along the way. 

Here are 4 specific examples: 

If we've been told repeatedly that we're not good at something, it can shape our perception of ourselves and our capabilities. 

If we've experienced failure in the past and it was met with negative consequences, it can make us associate failure with something negative. 

If we've grown up in an environment where failure was not tolerated, it can make us believe that failure is not an option. 

If we have a perfectionist mindset, we may feel like failure is unacceptable and can be too scared to even try something new. 

Now, the problem is when we act on these beliefs that we will fail, it can actually cause us to fail. Because, we limit ourselves and hold ourselves back from taking risks. 

And the only time you fail is when you give up. 

Otherwise, what you've experienced is actually a learning opportunity - and the more you know, the better you'll get and the easier it will become. 

So, next time you find yourself holding back because of the fear of failure, remember that failure is not a bad thing.

What to do when you feel like you’ve wasted your 20s spending all your money on booze, food and shoes, and you want to get your financial shit together in your 30s - from someone who’s gone from $40k debt to a millionaire at 30. 

First thing’s first, you’re going to need to start tracking your expenses. So many of our students think they have a handle on what they’re spending on, but through tracking their expenses they saw they were basically giving donations to billion dollar companies by paying for things they no longer use (like subscriptions), and things like overdraft or NSF fees for just not understanding when and how money was going in and out of their account. 

Next you’re going to start to build an emergency fund. Your credit card is not an emergency fund, it’s simply a tool that you can filter your expenses through to get perks, and protect yourself when you’re buying (some cards have things like purchase protection, which is like an insurance policy for whatever you bought). 

This should be a minimum 6 months of bare bones expenses. Keep this in a high yield savings account - I make about $100 a month for keeping my savings here. 

Pro tip: if big goals stress you out, break them down into smaller ones. Instead of thinking you need to save 6 months of expenses, figure out how much you need to save each month or paycheck to keep on track and skip the overwhelm. 

Third thing you’re going to do is pay off your high interest debt - anything over 6-7% needs to go, but I’d pay off the highest interest rates first. This is called the avalanche method. 

Fourth thing you’re going to do is start investing for your future - investing isn’t for the rich, it’s how you get rich… and it’s not only how you get rich, but the only real way to build financial safety and security long term. 

Your roth ira, 401k, rrsp, tfsa, those are not investments. Learning how to invest could build you hundreds of thousands of dollars of wealth with like $50 a month if you put it in the right places.

If American women earned minimum wage for the unpaid work they do around the house and caring for relatives, they would have made $1.5 trillion last year. ⁠
⁠
The New York Times looked at how much women would have made last year if they earned minimum wage for their unpaid work. The value of this shadow labor is staggering: $10.9 trillion, according to an analysis by Oxfam. ⁠
⁠
It exceeds the combined revenue of the 50 largest companies on last year’s Fortune Global 500 list, including Walmart, Apple and Amazon. And this is an important point to make, because while your partner may be pushing for finances to be EQUAL we know that the rest of life tasks (like the mental load or household responsibilities) may not be. ⁠
⁠
If you're feeling resentful towards your partner because you're paying half but doing a lot more, it might be time to start looking at an equitable way to divide things. ⁠
⁠
What does that mean? Say both parties work full time, but one makes $100,000 per year and the other makes $40,000. There's a large disparity between what could be deemed "affordable" for one and not the other. Equal means paying for things 50/50, while equitable means contributing what is fair (what is fair will be different to each couple, there is no right or wrong answer). ⁠
⁠
This could mean you split expenses: - right down the middle - each party pays a percentage of their income - each party takes on different expenses - you split shared expenses but pay for your own "extras" But when you're deciding on how to split your financial matters, it's important you also consider the unpaid additional contributions that are made, like carrying the mental load (having to plan everything, pay the bills, make sure things are done on time, essentially managing the household), and actual household tasks like cooking and cleaning. ⁠
⁠
When you split finances 50/50 but take on 100% of everything else, it could cause resentment or problems down the road. It's important to bring this issues to light and create a plan that feels good to everyone (I recommend money dates for this!)⁠
⁠

If you believe you have to work hard to make money, you always will. What you believe becomes the results you have in life. 
So if you believe you can't, or that it's too hard, it will be. Do you ever feel like no matter how hard you try, you just can't seem to get where you want to be in life? Our beliefs have a huge impact on our thoughts, actions, and ultimately, our results. Have you heard about the RAS (Reticular Activating System)? It's a part of our brain that acts like a filter, letting in information that is relevant to our beliefs and goals, while ignoring the rest. That's why if you have limiting financial beliefs, you're likely attracting more of the same into your life. A limiting financial belief is a belief you have that limits you in some way. Like... "Money is hard to come by" "I'm not good with money" "I'll never be rich" The first step to identifying limiting beliefs is to become aware of your thoughts. Pay attention to the things you tell yourself on a daily basis. Are they positive and empowering, or do they hold you back? If it's the latter, it's time to start challenging them. Next, ask yourself where these beliefs came from. Did you learn them from your parents, friends, or society? Are they based on past experiences or failures? Understanding the root of these beliefs can help you see them for what they are - just thoughts - and not absolute truths. Write down three ways your belief is untrue. Then it's time to replace those limiting beliefs with new, empowering ones. Write down positive affirmations that counter your old beliefs and repeat them to yourself daily. Surround yourself with people who believe in you and your abilities, and engage in activities that make you feel good about yourself. And remember, it takes time to change a belief, so be patient and persistent! Here's how you could rewrite them so they serve you: "Money flows easily and effortlessly into my life" "I am financially savvy and capable" "I am worthy of financial abundance and success" Write these on your mirror, make them the background on your phone, put them somewhere you'll see them all the time and say them out loud with conviction. Hey bestie, Remember when you were younger and you always had to pretend like everything was fine even when it wasn't? 

I know it was tough for you, but did you ever think about how that could be affecting you now? See, not being able to talk about money problems can lead to some serious financial anxiety as we get older. 

It's like we learn to keep everything bottled up inside, and even the thought of money can make us feel overwhelmed and stressed. 

Here are three examples of why financial anxiety can occur based on what we experienced as children: 

Fear of not having enough: When we were younger, we might have experienced times when our family didn't have enough money to cover basic necessities like food or rent. That feeling of uncertainty and insecurity can stick with us, even if we're financially stable now. 

Shame and embarrassment: Maybe our parents were always worried about what the neighbors or relatives would think if they found out about our family's money problems. We might have internalized that shame and embarrassment, making it hard to talk about money with anyone, even close friends. 

Lack of financial education: When we're not allowed to talk about money, we miss out on valuable lessons about making money, saving, and investing. That can leave us feeling unprepared and overwhelmed when we have to make important financial decisions as adults. 

I just wanted to remind you that it's okay to talk about money and ask for help when you need it. We don't have to keep everything inside like we did when we were younger. 

I'm here for you, always. 💕

Falling victim to the classic "I'll just put it on my credit card and pay it off next payday" move. 

You know, the one where next payday comes around and suddenly you're completely broke, with no cash to pay off your debt. 

We've all been there, and it can feel like there's no way out. But here's the thing: getting out of credit card debt isn't just about learning the avalanche method or making more money (although those can definitely help). 

It's about addressing the underlying reasons you were in debt in the first place. If you never get to the root of the problem, you'll be stuck in a vicious cycle of paying down your debt and wracking it back up again. 

There are so many reasons why someone might go into credit card debt - maybe it's: 

🛍 impulse shopping because you're unhappy at work and you're looking for a "pick me up" 

🛍 overspending to fill an emotional void, because you've been struggling in your relationships and you just want something that makes you "feel good"

Let's talk about financial inequalities between men and women. Did you know that in 2021, women in the United States earn only 82 cents for every dollar earned by men? 

And that's just the tip of the iceberg. For centuries, women have been systematically excluded from economic opportunities and denied the right to own property, access credit and financial services, and participate fully in the economy. 

For example, did you know that it wasn't until 1974 that the Equal Credit Opportunity Act was passed, which made it illegal for lenders to discriminate against women when issuing credit? 

Before that, women couldn't get credit cards or loans without a male co-signer, and were often denied loans altogether because they were considered a "bad risk" due to their gender. 

And even earlier in history, women were not allowed to own property. In fact, it wasn't until the mid-19th century that women in the United States began to gain legal rights to property ownership. 

This means that for centuries, women were unable to accumulate wealth or build financial security through property ownership. 

These historical factors, along with ongoing discrimination and gender bias in the workforce, have contributed to the significant wealth gap between men and women. 

In fact, the average woman in the United States has only 32 cents in wealth for every dollar owned by a man. 

It's time to acknowledge and address these systemic inequalities. 

We need policies and practices that promote gender equality in the workforce, provide greater access to credit and financial services for women, and ensure that women have equal rights to own and control property. 

Let's work together to build a more equitable and just financial system for all. 

So, when you suggest that women shouldn't have financial content tailored to them, you're ignoring the fact that women face systemic financial barriers that need to be addressed. It's time to acknowledge these issues and work towards creating a more equitable financial system. 

And until then, women deserve financial content that speaks directly to their unique experiences and challenges.

Are you ready to hear the truth about why investing when you're young is so incredibly powerful? 

Let me break it down for you. The magic of investing when you're young lies in the power of compound interest. With compound interest, you not only earn interest on the money you invest, but you also earn interest on the interest you earn. It's like a snowball effect, and the earlier you start, the bigger your snowball can grow. 

But don't just take my word for it. Let's look at an example. Say you invest $5,000 at age 25, and you earn an average annual return of 7%. If you keep that money invested for 40 years, by the time you're 65, you'll have over $52,000. But if you wait until you're 35 to invest that same amount, you'll end up with around $28,000 - almost HALF. 

That's the power of compound interest! 

And that's not all. When you invest when you're young, you have time on your side. You can weather market ups and downs and take more risks, knowing that you have decades ahead of you to recover from any losses. 

Plus, the more you invest when you're young, the less you have to save later on in life to achieve your financial goals. 

So, why is compound interest so beautiful? It's because it's a simple but incredibly powerful concept that can make your money work harder for you. And the earlier you start, the more time your money has to grow. 

In fact, did you know that money you save and invest in your 20s is worth twice as much as money you save and invest in your 30s due to compound interest?

What does it mean when stock futures are up? 

When people talk about stock futures being up, it means that investors expect the stock market to go up in the future. Stock futures are a prediction of how stocks will perform on the stock market in the coming days or weeks. 

If stock futures are up, it usually means that investors are feeling optimistic about the economy and the companies whose stocks they're buying. 

However, it's important to remember that stock futures are just a prediction, and the actual performance of stocks on the market can be influenced by many factors.

 What many people don't understand is:

👉 markets always go up and down 
👉 crashes are normal and to be expected 
👉 you still own the same number of shares (stocks), they're just worth less for a moment in time 
👉 you only lose money if you aren't diversified properly (all your eggs are in one basket) or you SELL - the act of selling is what actually locks in your losses 

The whole point of investing is buying assets at a lower price, and then selling them at a higher price. That's how you make money.

I don't keep my savings in a regular checking or savings account anymore because let's face it, that's a great way to LOSE money to inflation! 💸 

Instead, I invest my money and make it GROW while I sleep. Here are 5 reasons why you shouldn't keep your savings in a regular bank account: 

1️⃣ Low interest rates - most banks offer a measly interest rate of less than 1%, meaning your money isn't even keeping up with inflation. 

2️⃣ Inflation - inflation is currently at an all-time high, meaning the value of your money is decreasing over time. 

3️⃣ Opportunity cost - while your money sits in a bank account, you're missing out on potential investment opportunities that could grow your wealth exponentially. 

4️⃣ High-yield savings accounts - if you're going to keep your money in a bank account, at the very least make sure it's in a high-yield savings account. I make about $100 a month off of the interest from mine! 

5️⃣ Financial goals - if you have any financial goals, like retirement, you'll never reach them by keeping your money in a low-interest bank account. 

If you're saving for something shorter term like a house, car or vacation, you could get that money into a CD/GIC to help it grow (I have a GIC right now from EQ Bank that is paying me 5% GUARANTEED over the next year 💯).

Let's talk about feeling like we are always one purchase away from happiness, and the Diderot effect. 

Have you ever bought a new handbag and then suddenly felt like your whole wardrobe was outdated? Or maybe you got a new iPhone and all of a sudden your laptop just wasn't cutting it anymore? 

Well, welcome to the wild world of the Diderot Effect. This phenomenon is named after a French philosopher who noticed that having one fancy new item often leads to wanting more and more luxurious possessions. 

It's like a never-ending cycle of consumption and materialism that can leave you feeling unsatisfied and unhappy. 

But don't worry, you're not alone in this! We all fall into this trap from time to time, but the key to overcoming it is to be mindful and intentional about your purchases. 

Here are a few tips for breaking free from the Diderot Effect: 

Make a list of your needs and wants: Before you make a purchase, take a moment to think about what you actually need and what you just want. 

Practice gratitude: Instead of always focusing on what you don't have, take a moment to appreciate what you do have. 

Invest in experiences: Instead of always buying things, consider investing in experiences that will bring you joy and happiness. 

Don't let the Diderot Effect hold you back! By being intentional about your purchases and focusing on what truly brings you happiness, you'll be able to break free from this cycle and live a more fulfilling life.

I went from broke girl to rich girl by learning how to invest. 

Let's break down the top 10 terms you need to know to become a millionaire. 

Stocks: This is where you buy a piece of a company and become a part owner, then you get paid when they do well. 

Bonds: This is when you loan your money to the government or a company, and you get paid interest. 

Index Funds/ETFs: These are baskets of stocks. Instead of trying to figure out which one company is best, you can just buy one of these. 

Mutual Funds: These are also baskets of stocks, but they're high fee and they don't beat the market. So you pay more to make less. 

Dividends: This is when companies share their profits with you, it's money that just shows up into your account for you owning the stock. 

Capital Gains: This is the profit you make when you sell a stock or other investment for more than you bought it. So if you bought a stock for $50 and sold it for $100, you'd have a $50 capital gain. 

Volatility: This is when the price of an investment goes up and down quickly, in the short term stock prices change a lot, the long term is where you make money (5+ years). 

Portfolio: This is the collection of investments that you have. 

Diversifying: This is when you spread out your money so you reduce your risk, it means not putting all your eggs in one basket. To do this you can get different types of investments, in different industries, in different countries, over time. 

Asset Allocation: This is how much you have of each type of investment. Typically when you're younger you can have a more "risky" asset allocation, meaning more stocks, because you have more time to ride the waves of the market before you need the money. This can result in you making more.

It's the idea that what you believe to be true will become true for you. 

And when it comes to money, our attitudes and beliefs around money are shaped by the time we're 7 years old. 

That means we use these beliefs to run our lives as adults, and if we never update them, we'll continue to run our lives based on the things we saw and perceived as children. 😳

1️⃣ If you believe that you'll never be good with money, you'll likely continue to make choices that confirm that belief. But if you believe that you can learn to be good with money, you'll start to seek out resources and opportunities to improve your financial situation. 

2️⃣ If you believe that you always have to struggle to make ends meet, you'll likely feel stuck in a cycle of scarcity. But if you believe that abundance is possible, you'll start to see opportunities to create more wealth and prosperity in your life.

The way we grow up and the things we hear as children can have a significant impact on our financial habits as adults. 

For example, if you grew up hearing phrases like "money doesn't grow on trees" or "we can't afford that," you might develop a scarcity mindset, which can lead to overspending. 

This scarcity mindset can make us feel like we need to spend now or else we may never get the chance again. 

It can create a sense of urgency around spending, which can lead to impulse buys and overspending. 

It can also make us feel like we need to keep up with the Joneses, even if we can't afford to do so, because we don't want to feel like we're missing out. 

Another way that childhood experiences can impact our spending habits is through emotional spending. 

For example, if you grew up in a household where gifts and material possessions were used as a way to show love and affection, you might have learned to associate buying things with feeling good. 

This can lead to emotional spending, where we buy things to fill an emotional void or make ourselves feel better. 

Understanding the psychology and mindset behind overspending is the first step in overcoming it. 

By recognizing the underlying beliefs and emotions that drive our spending habits, we can start to make more conscious choices about how we use our money.

While the S&P 500 is undoubtedly one of the most well-known and widely followed stock market indexes, it's important to understand that it doesn't represent a complete or diversified portfolio. Here's why: 

1️⃣ Lack of Global Exposure: The S&P 500 is primarily focused on the largest publicly traded U.S. companies, which means it overlooks opportunities outside the United States. A truly diversified portfolio should consider international markets, providing exposure to different regions and industries. 

2️⃣ Sector Concentration: The S&P 500 is market-cap-weighted, meaning larger companies have a more significant influence. Consequently, certain sectors, such as technology or finance, may dominate the index. Overreliance on a specific sector increases vulnerability to sector-specific risks and potential downturns. 

3️⃣ Omission of Small Caps: The S&P 500 primarily includes large-cap stocks, neglecting the smaller companies. Small-cap stocks can offer unique growth opportunities and help diversify risk by tapping into different market segments. 

4️⃣ Non-Inclusion of Other Asset Classes: The S&P 500 focuses solely on stocks, overlooking other asset classes like bonds, real estate, commodities, and alternative investments. Including a variety of assets can help mitigate risk and improve the overall stability of your portfolio.

Looking for a hands-off way to invest for retirement? 💼✨ Look no further than Target Date Funds! 🎯📈 

Let's break it down: 

Target Date Fund: A target date fund is an investment that automatically adjusts its asset allocation based on your projected retirement date. It's designed to be a set-it-and-forget-it approach, making it perfect for those who want a hassle-free investing experience. 

Ticker Symbol: Ticker symbols are short form names for investments. This is what you would use to search the investment when you want to buy it at your brokerage. 

When investing in a target date fund, it's essential to do your research outside of your brokerage app to find the appropriate fund for your retirement goals. 

How does a Target Date Fund work? 🤔💼 A target date fund is designed to automatically adjust its asset allocation (how many stocks versus bonds you own) as you approach your retirement date. 

When you're young, the fund will generally have a higher allocation towards stocks, which tend to have higher potential returns but also higher volatility (you'll see the prices go up and down more in the short term). 

As you get closer to retirement, the fund will gradually shift its allocation towards more conservative investments like bonds. This strategy is designed to reduce risk as you approach your target retirement date. 

The beauty of a target date fund lies in its simplicity. By investing in one, you can just set it and forget it. 

The fund will make adjustments over time, rebalancing the portfolio to maintain an appropriate risk level.

Did you know that the cost to attend a university has skyrocketed nearly eight times faster than our wages did? 😱 

Between 1989 and 2016, the cost of a four-year degree exploded to a staggering $104,480, while real median wages only increased from $54,042 to $59,039. This means that each successive cohort of graduates is worse off than the last. 🎓💔 

It's no wonder so many of us are struggling with student loan debt! We were told that going to school was the key to success, but now we find ourselves feeling like we're drowning in debt. I want to extend my empathy to those who thought their loans would be forgiven by the Biden Administration. I honestly never believed it would go all the way through, but it sucks, plain and simple. 

The reason it was blocked in the Supreme Court was due to Biden v. Nebraska, where the president's plan was challenged by six Republican-led states. They argued that debt relief would hurt their states' tax revenues (THEY'LL ALWAYS GET THAT TAX MONEY) and MOHELA, a student-loan company based in Missouri, who didn't even know they were being named in the lawsuit. 🏛️💼 

But let's not lose hope! Now that student loan payments will resume, I want to share three important steps we can take: 

1️⃣ First, I know it's tough, but we have to face our loan balances head-on. Understanding the interest rates and minimum payments is crucial to managing our debt effectively. Log into your accounts, check your balances, minimum payments, and who you owe what to. 

2️⃣ If you've been setting aside your student loan payments while they were paused into a HYSA (this was my recommendation), now you have a lump sum to put against those loans. 

You can actually call and request that it be directly applied to the loan principle! 🏦📞 

3️⃣ Lastly, let's invest in our financial knowledge. The more we know about managing money, the better equipped we are to make more, save more, pay off those loans faster, and start building our wealth through smart investments. 

Education is not just about degrees; it's about empowering ourselves financially.

HOW SHOULD YOU SPLIT EXPENSES IN A RELATIONSHIP? 👇👇 

Let's chat about the differences between equal (50/50) and equitable when it comes to household responsibilities. 

It's important to remember that achieving financial fairness is more than just splitting bills. It's about security, teamwork, and a willingness to share. 💑💬⁣ 

Here's the scoop: Equality means treating everyone the same, while equity ensures everyone has the chance for similar outcomes. 📊💡 Studies suggest that equity tends to be the fairer outcome, as it considers different starting points and circumstances.⁣ 

So how does financial equity look in relationships? It involves adjusting expenses based on each person's income, valuing unpaid labor, and ensuring both partners have a say in money matters without guilt or allowances. 🤝💕⁣ 

Why does this matter? Well, outside of relationships, we can see the effects of inequity, like the gender pay gap. It's essential to achieve financial fairness to avoid negative impacts like financial stress and lower quality of life.⁣ 

When there's an earning disparity, equity becomes even more crucial. Women, in particular, can be disadvantaged if financial equity isn't achieved, facing potential challenges in retirement and beyond (due to circumstances like the motherhood penalty). 

If you're working towards financial equity, start by having open conversations as a team, understanding each other's values, and setting joint goals. 

Remember, there's no one-size-fits-all approach, but understanding the difference between equal and equitable can help you create a stronger financial foundation for your relationship. 

The goal is to thrive, not just survive.

Picture this... You find out you're going to need surgery and you're given two options.

I used to be the queen of impulse shopping - but learning how to set financial boundaries with myself totally changed the game.

Here are 13 questions to ask before you hit that "buy now" button, so you can stop overspending and start building your dream life.

Do I really need this item or is it just a want or desire?

Can I afford to buy this item without putting myself in financial strain?

Am I buying this item to impress others or to fit in with a certain crowd?

Will this item bring long-term value to my life or is it just a short-term pleasure?

How often will I use or wear this item? Is it worth the investment?

Is this an expense (something that just takes money out of my life) or an investment (something that pays me back, either financially, or emotionally) - always consider the ROI.

Is there somewhere else I would have rather spent the money? Maybe that girls trip in 3 months feel better and provide a better ROI?

Can I find this item for a lower price elsewhere or can I wait for it to go on sale? A principle I teach is WPM, essentially if you can get the same benefit for less, WHY PAY MORE FOR IT?

Ask yourself - what is the actual benefit to my life? Does it serve me, grow me or make me happy?

Do I have space for this item in my home or will it just add to clutter?

Is buying this item in line with my financial goals and priorities?

How will I feel about this purchase a week or a month from now?

Am I making this purchase out of boredom, stress, or other emotional reasons?

No one is talking about this investment, but it's helped me make 6 figures a year in cash flow and become financially free in my 30s. 

Let's talk. 

A MIC is a mortgage investment corporation, basically I pool my money with other investors to loan out and I get paid the interest. 

Some of these can be super risky, so you need to make sure you do your research before you start - I'm going to go over a few that I would never invest in at the end of the video. 

When you're thinking about making any investment, you want to be doing it from a defensive standpoint. Remember how you were taught to drive defensively, because you can't control the other people on the road? That's how we invest. We can't control the market, but we can control our actions to keep our money safe. 

So, we need to go into every investment decision thinking: how do I make sure I don't lose money? 

Here are some key factors I look at: 

Loan to value ratio: this is how much of the value of the home is being loaned out. The higher the ratio, the higher the risk. 

Mortgage position: this determines who gets paid out first when the house is sold, there can be first, second and third mortgages. The higher the position, the higher the risk. 

Borrower: you need to understand who is getting these mortgages and why. Is it because they're blue collar workers and getting paid under the table, so they're not showing enough income to get a loan from a regular bank, or is it because they're a credit risk, or trying to finance something the banks won't?

On this episode of stuff they should have taught you in school because it will completely change your life, we're talking about the Rule of 72.

And this is so crazy it almost feels illegal.

Albert Einstein once said that compound interest is the 8th wonder of the world, he who understands it earns it, but he who doesn't pays it.

And compound interest is just the thing that's going to make you rich. Look at this:

The rule of 72 says if you divide the interest rate you are getting by 72, it tells you how long it will take for your money to double. 

Let's say you had $10,000 in a regular savings account where the average return is 0.55, it will take 130 years for your money to double.

But, if you put your $10,000 into the stock market, earning an average 10% a year, it will only take 7 years for your money to double.

The growth after this is exponential.

Because while it took 7 years for your $10,000 to turn into $20,000, it will only take 7 years to turn that $20,000 in to $40,000, then that $40,000 into $80,000.

This concept is how you can turn $50 a month into hundreds of thousands of dollars in free money, and is why getting to the golden goose bank account of $100k by 35 means you'll retire a millionaire even if you never saved another dollar.

1️⃣ **It's Highly Speculative:** Crypto's value isn't rooted in a tangible asset or company. It's driven by market sentiment. You're essentially betting on whether someone else will find it more valuable than what you paid for it.

2️⃣ **Lack of Income Generation:** When you invest in stocks or real estate, you're buying into something that generates income – dividends, rent, or profit from a business. Crypto doesn't do that.

3️⃣ **Risk of Pure Speculation:** Sure, some folks have made money in crypto, just like some people win the lottery. Winning once doesn't guarantee it'll happen again. I'd rather not rely on luck.

💰 Let's talk about something SUPER IMPORTANT today – avoiding costly investing mistakes that could set you back hundreds of thousands of dollars. 😱

🚫 **Mistake 1: Confusing Accounts with Investments** 🚫

Your 401ks, IRAs, RRSPs, and TFSAs are NOT investments themselves. They're like special containers that hold your investments. Confusing them can lead to missing out on any growth inside your account.

You need to buy investments within your account to see your money grow, otherwise it's just losing value due to inflation.

🤔 **The Fix:** Understand what's inside these accounts. Are you invested in stocks, bonds, or other assets? Diversify wisely based on your goals!

🚀 **Mistake 2: Playing it Too Safe for Too Long** 🚀

Being in low-risk funds when you're years or even decades away from retirement can actually be riskier! You might miss out on the growth potential that can secure your future.

⏳ **The Fix:** Assess your risk tolerance and adjust your portfolio accordingly. Time is your ally for long-term growth.

When you're younger and have more years before retirement, you can afford to take more "risk". The bigger risk becomes not having enough money to ever stop working when you're investing in "safe" or "balanced" funds in your 20s and 30s.

💸 **Mistake 3: Falling for High-Cost Mutual Funds** 💸

Every percent in fees matters! High-cost mutual funds can eat away at your returns. A mere 1% difference in fees could mean a decade less of retirement income. Ouch!

💡 **The Fix:** Opt for low-cost index funds or ETFs. They offer similar market exposure with significantly lower fees, leaving more money in your pocket.

Let's talk about the psychology behind inaction, and how understanding your tradeoff costs can be the difference between staying stuck and hitting your goals.

🚫 **Loss Aversion:** Our brains are wired to despise losses more than they value gains. When we recognize the cost of inaction, it becomes a powerful motivator. Think about it: What opportunities could slip away if we don't take action? 😱

⏰ **Temporal Discounting:** We tend to prioritize immediate pleasure over future rewards. That quick indulgence might be tempting, but it often stands in the way of our long-term goals. Keep your focus on the bigger picture! 🌟

🖼️ **Visualization & Contrast:** Picture your success vividly – living your dream life. Now, contrast it with the potential outcomes of inaction – dreams left unfulfilled and chances missed. This mental exercise is a catalyst for change!

🎯 **Goal Alignment:** Aligning your daily actions with your long-term goals is key. Don't let momentary comfort derail your journey. Remember, that daily grind is what paves the way to your success! 🏢

😬 **Cognitive Dissonance:** That uneasy feeling when you don't take action? It's your inner wisdom pushing you to resolve the conflict. Embrace it as a sign that you're ready for transformation!

💳 Boost Your Credit Score: Lower Your Credit Utilization to Save Money Effortlessly 

Why is a good credit score crucial? 🤔 Well, it can save you big bucks! With a lower score, you end up shelling out more in interest on things like student loans, car loans, and mortgages. Forbes did the math, and the difference is staggering – borrowers with a fair score can pay over TWICE as much in interest on various loans and a whopping 97% more on their credit cards! 😱

Now, let's dive into the nitty-gritty of what makes up your credit score.

 There are 5 key factors:

1️⃣ Payment History (35% of your score)
2️⃣ Amounts Owed (30% of your score) - aka credit utilization
3️⃣ Length of Credit History (15% of your score)
4️⃣ Credit Mix (10% of your score)
5️⃣ New Credit (10% of your score)

Today, we're putting the spotlight on factor #2 because it's a biggie and can be improved quickly. 😎

Imagine this scenario: You have a credit card with a $10,000 limit, and your current balance is $4,500. That makes your credit utilization 45%. But here's the magic number: We want to keep it under 30% to give your credit score a boost! ✨

💰 Quick Math Time 💰
$10,000 * 30% = $3,000

So, 30% of $10,000 is $3,000. To get that credit score boost, here are two strategies:

1️⃣ Pay down your balance by $1,500 if you can. 🔄
2️⃣ If you can't do that right away, consider increasing your credit limit (only if you trust yourself not to rack up more debt).

Let's say you raise your limit to $15,000. Now that $4,500 balance is back to that magical 30%! 🌟

Avoiding Financial Disaster: Why a Bad Agent Can Cost You Thousands in Home Purchases

I recently had an alarming call during a financial coaching session. A student shared her plan to invest in a property, but upon closer inspection, I spotted major red flags that her agent hadn't pointed out. High maintenance fees, potential legal issues, and a long time on the market were just the tip of the iceberg.

What bothered me most? The lack of due diligence by her agent. Not understanding the property's true value or ensuring it aligned with the condo laws is a recipe for financial disaster.

Ever heard of "fiduciary duty"? It's crucial. The seller's agent doesn't owe buyers the same loyalty they give to the seller. That means critical details might slip through the cracks - and her agent was relying on the seller for important information they should have been looking into themselves.

Worse yet, her agent didn't advise on a value range for the offer. Overpaying spells trouble; the bank won't cover more than the property's worth. That gap falls on the buyer, potentially costing a fortune.

Your agent should be more than a transaction broker. They're your guide, protector, and advocate. Whether it's your dream home or an investment property, choose wisely. Don't settle for someone who's in it for a quick commission. Your financial future depends on it.

Remember, the success of your home purchase often hinges on the competence and integrity of your real estate agent. Do your homework before entrusting them with your biggest investment. Your financial well-being is worth it!

Is renting throwing your money away?

No, it can be a strategic move that fuels your financial future. 

While I personally lean towards homeownership for various reasons, let's dive into the numbers. 

Homeownership comes with unrecoverable costs— usually around 5% of a home's value annually, covering things like insurance, property taxes, and maintenance. 

These are pure expenses, and money you will not get back. 

The argument that is always made against renting is that you never get any of your rent back (making the entire amount an "unrecoverable cost"). 

Here's the trick: if you can rent a property for less than this 5% in unrecoverable costs you'd pay to own a home, and invest the difference, you're on a solid financial track. 

Yes a home may appreciate (the past decade is NOT normal, avg appreciation is closer to the rate of inflation, ie. ~3% annually), but it's not a cash-generating asset; it's a liability because it will never pay you, you will always pay for it. 

Whereas your investments in the stock market (the difference you saved) can grow at an average rate of ~10% (using the historical returns of the total market over the last century).

(unless you've purchased with a wealth building strategy like house hacking, your house is simply something you pay for)

Additionally, owning is not the right situation for every person in every situation - and buying when it doesn't make sense simply because of the cognitive bias "owning is always better", can be the reason you lose a lot of money.

(I've worked on the sale of hundreds of homes when I was a Broker, and have seen this firsthand - even in hot housing markets).

Whether you rent or own, there's a path to financial success.

If you're in Canada and you're planning on buying a home in the next 15 years, here's how you can save thousands on your taxes to help you beef up your down payment or save for other financial goals. 

If you thought we already paid enough in taxes at a time when everyone is feeling the pinch of inflation, the Canadian government says: nope, we think you can pay more. 

The rich know that one of the best ways to save money is to limit the amount of taxes they pay, that's why so many of them own businesses, but for people who work a regular 9-5, what options do they have? 

One is something called the FHSA account, which is essentially an investing account made for first time home buyers to assist them in saving for a down payment on their first property. The beautiful thing about this account is that any money you put into it is tax deductible, meaning you get a write off on your taxes, which reduces how much you have to pay. 

If you open an account before December 31, you will accrue $8000 in contribution room. If you made, for example, $70,000 a year in Ontario, contributing the full $8,000 means you'd bring the amount of money you have to pay in taxes down from $12,847 to $10,475 saving you $2,372 in taxes. 

Once you got that refund, you could put that right into your FHSA to add a couple thousand to your down payment, and get this: that $2,372 would be a deduction on your taxes for 2024 saving you even more money. 

The even better part? Invest that money into the stock market for long term or GICs for short term timelines, and all of the money you make is also tax free. It's like the benefits of the RRSP and TFSA combined. 

Even if you don't have the money to contribute right now, I'd still open the account so you can gain the $8,000 contribution room for 2023.

🔍 The Biggest Mistake in Tax Season 📊💸 

One of the most common mistakes during tax time is misunderstanding the difference between a write-off and a personal expense. 🤔 

Let's break it down: Write-off vs. Personal Expense: A write-off refers to expenses that are considered ordinary and necessary for your business. 

On the other hand, personal expenses are those that aren't directly related to your business activities. Remember, you can only deduct what's essential for your business operations. 

Let's look at an example. 

✍️ How it Works for a Writer: As a writer, your business expenses might include research materials, office supplies, or even a portion of your workspace. 

However, claiming these expenses doesn't mean the government pays you. It reduces your taxable income. 

For instance: 💰 Someone earning $100,000 yearly, with $5,000 in business expenses, brings down their taxable income to $95,000. They pay taxes on that reduced $95,000 amount, not the initial $100,000. 

💡 **But remember,** that $5,000 isn't free money. It's money spent on business necessities, which still comes out of the income earned in the business.

🐒 Have you heard of the Monkey Ladder Experiment? 🍌 Get ready for a paradigm shift!

Let me tell you about how challenging societal norms transformed my life, leading me to happiness and unexpected riches.

Picture a room full of monkeys and a tempting bunch of bananas atop a ladder. Whenever a monkey attempts to climb for the bananas, they all receive a spritz of water. Soon enough, they stop each other from climbing to avoid the spray.

Now, the fascinating part: new monkeys replace the originals, unaware of the water consequence. Despite never experiencing the spray, they still prevent any monkey from climbing the ladder.
